# Engineering Principles

Write code that is correct by construction. Prefer the compiler/type-checker catching bugs over tests over humans.

## Types First

- Define or update types/interfaces BEFORE writing logic
- Use enums/unions for domain concepts (status, currency, payment type) — never raw strings
- Make invalid states unrepresentable: if it compiles/type-checks, it's valid
- Exhaustive matching — no catch-all `_ =>` or `default:` that silently swallows new variants

## Error Handling

- Every error path must be explicitly handled — no swallowing errors
- Rust: no `.unwrap()` / `.expect()` in production; use `?` or `map_err`
- TypeScript: every API call handles both success and error; no empty `catch {}`
- Design errors as typed variants, not string messages

## Auth & Security

- Every handler that accepts auth MUST verify the user is authorized for the SPECIFIC resource, not just authenticated
- Never suppress or skip authorization checks

## Frontend ↔ Backend Contract

- The backend uses `#[serde(rename_all = "camelCase")]` — Rust `snake_case` fields become `camelCase` in JSON
- When sending data TO the backend, map frontend field names to the backend's expected camelCase names (e.g. `type` → `offerType`, `type` → `paymentType`)
- When receiving data FROM the backend, map backend field names back (e.g. `paymentType` → `type`)
- Always check the backend Rust struct definition to confirm exact field names before writing API calls
- Backend list endpoints may return flat arrays; don't assume `{ items: [...], total }` wrappers

## Pure Logic, Side Effects at the Edges

- Core domain logic should be pure and testable without IO or mocks
- Push side effects (API calls, DB, network) to the boundaries (handlers, hooks, pages)
- Immutable by default

## Testing

- Tests make real assertions about specific values — not just "status != 404"
- Property tests > integration > unit (Rust); integration > unit (frontend)
- All tests pass before pushing

## Commit Discipline

- One logical change per commit
- Message describes what AND why
- Build passes before pushing — no "fix build" follow-up chains
- Never include secrets in commits
